<SubSection title="Shear Stress and Strain"></SubSection>

<SubSubSection title="Shear Strain: Geometry of Deformation">

<Image src="/mechref/Solid_Mechanics/Torsion-Figures/GeometryDeformation.png" width="4">  <BlueText>Taken from TAM251 Lecture Notes - L5S6</BlueText></Image>

 The angle of twist increases as x increases. The twist rate is given by: <DisplayEquation equation="\\frac{d\\phi}{dx} = \\frac{\\gamma}{\\rho} = \\frac{\\gamma_{max}}{c}\\" />

 Moving terms we get:<DisplayEquation equation="\\gamma = \\rho \\frac{d\\phi}{dx}\\" />

 Hence, the shear strain (<InlineEquation equation="\\gamma" />):
<Itemize>
    <Item> is proportional to the angle of twist</Item>
    <Item> varies linearly with the distance from the axis of the shaft</Item>
    <Item> is <strong>maximum</strong> at the surface</Item>
</Itemize>

</SubSubSection>

<SubSubSection title="Shear Stress: Torsion Formula">

Geometry: <DisplayEquation equation="\\gamma = \\rho \\frac{d\\phi}{dx}\\" />

 Hooke's Law: <DisplayEquation equation="\\tau = G\\gamma\\" />

 From equilibrium: <DisplayEquation equation="\\frac{d\\phi}{dx} = \\frac{T}{GJ}\\" />

 Elastic torsion formula: <DisplayEquation equation="\\tau = \\frac{T\\rho}{J}\\" />

 <BlueText>The shear stress in the elastic range varies linearly with the radial position in the section</BlueText>

<Image src="/mechref/Solid_Mechanics/Torsion-Figures/StressDistribution.png" width="4">  <BlueText>Taken from TAM251 Lecture Notes - L5S8</BlueText></Image>

 <BlueText><em>Note:</em>  shaft under torque T rotating at angular speed w transmits power  
 <DisplayEquation equation="P=T\\omega\\" /></BlueText>

</SubSubSection>

<SubSubSection title="Shear Stress: Polar Moment of Inertia">

Solid Shaft (radius and diameter): <DisplayEquation equation="J = \\int_0^R{\\rho^2dA} = \\int_0^R{\\rho^2(2\\pi\\rho d\\rho)dA} =2\\pi \\int_0^R{\\rho^3d\\rho} = \\frac{\\pi R^4}{2} = \\frac{\\pi D^4}{32}\\" />

 Hollow Shaft (inner and outer radius): <DisplayEquation equation="J = \\frac{\\pi}{2}(R_o^4-R_i^4) = \\frac{\\pi}{32}(D_o^4-D_i^4)\\" />
</SubSubSection>

